Val-de-Marne (French pronunciation: [&#91;val də maʁn&#93;](/Help:IPA/French) [ⓘ](/File:Fr-Paris--Val-de-Marne.ogg) , "Vale of the [Marne](/Marne_(river))") is a [department of France](/Departments_of_France) located in the [Île-de-France](/%C3%8Ele-de-France) [region](/Regions_of_France). Named after the river [Marne](/Marne_(river)), it is situated in the [Grand Paris](/Grand_Paris) [metropolis](/M%C3%A9tropole) to the southeast of [Paris](/Paris)’ city centre. In 2019, Val-de-Marne had a population of 1,407,124. &#91;4&#93;  

Its [INSEE](/Institut_national_de_la_statistique_et_des_%C3%A9tudes_%C3%A9conomiques) and postcode number is 94.  

## Geography  

Val-de-Marne is, together with [Seine-Saint-Denis](/Seine-Saint-Denis) and [Hauts-de-Seine](/Hauts-de-Seine), one of three small departments in Île-de-France that form a ring around Paris, known as the [Petite Couronne](/%C3%8Ele-de-France) ("inner ring"). Since 1 January 2016, Val-de-Marne is included in the [Métropole du Grand Paris](/Grand_Paris).  

The territory stretches from the banks of the Seine to the forested hills of the [Forêt de Fontainebleau](/For%C3%AAt_de_Fontainebleau) and includes a substantial portion of the [Marne](/Marne_(river)) valley. Its landscape is characterised by a mix of dense urban zones, industrial corridors, and green spaces, notably the [Roseraie de L'Haÿ](/Roseraie_de_L%27Ha%C3%AF) and the [Vincennes Racecourse](/Vincennes_Racecourse).  

The department’s altitude varies modestly, with the lowest points near the river at roughly 20 m above sea level and the highest points in the southern woods reaching about 150 m. The climate is a temperate oceanic one, featuring mild winters and warm summers, though the urban heat island effect can raise local temperatures compared with surrounding rural areas.  

