## Administration  

•  
See also: [Departmental Council of Val-de-Marne](/Departmental_Council_of_Val-de-Marne)  

Val-de-Marne is made up of 3 [departmental arrondissements](/Arrondissements_of_France) and 47 [communes](/Communes_of_France):  

* [Arrondissement of L'Haÿ-les-Roses](/Arrondissement_of_L%27Ha%C3%AF-les-Roses) – includes the communes listed above.  
* [Arrondissement of Créteil](/Arrondissement_of_Cr%C3%A9teil) – includes the communes listed above.  
* [Arrondissement of Nogent‑sur‑Marne](/Arrondissement_of_Nogent-sur-Marne) – includes the communes listed above.  

The departmental council is presided over by Olivier Capitanio, elected in July 2021.  

## History  

Val-de-Marne was created in January 1968, through the implementation of a law passed in July 1964. Positioned to the south‑east of the [Paris ring road](/Boulevard_P%C3%A9riph%C3%A9rique) (and the line of the [old city walls](/Thiers_wall)), it was formed from the southern‑eastern part of the (previously much larger) [Seine department](/Seine_(department)), together with a small portion taken from the broken‑up department of [Seine-et-Oise](/Seine-et-Oise).  

The new department inherited much of the administrative infrastructure from its predecessors, including the historic [Château de Vincennes](/Ch%C3%A2teau_de_Vincennes) which now serves as a symbolic landmark rather than a seat of government.  

